english:
  title: Farewell to the Great Chan Master Haiyun of Fusang, Zhongshan Daoyin
  author: Yu Mun-tong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Fusang lies a thousand leagues away,
    Yet wooden paths connect the sea.
    When envoys now bear word from court,
    Distant lands long answer to our call.

    The Chan master's mind rests in true stillness,
    Illusion's nature returns to emptiness.
    At dawn his verses harmonize with meter's grace,
    His bearing dignified in every turn.

    Observing splendid culture's bloom,
    He witnessed glory's fullest crown.
    Though royal tasks knew hardship's way,
    Let bonds between our nations hold.

    Joy lingers, warm and lingering still,
    Yet homeward longing stirs the heart.
    On island shores, green mist hangs thick,
    While sunset pours in crimson streams.

    The boat glides light as falling leaf,
    The sail moves swifter than the goose.
    Home draws near with every stroke—
    The pine branch points toward the East.
  footnotes:
    - Fusang (扶桑) is a classical name for Japan, derived from ancient Chinese geographical texts.
    - The poem uses 'wooden paths' (木道) to refer to maritime routes of commerce and diplomacy.
    - Chan (禪) refers to Zen Buddhism; the master embodies both spiritual refinement and cultural sophistication.
    - The final image of the pine branch pointing east is a poetic departure, suggesting the master's return journey toward his homeland.
